Preheat your oven to 220°C. Slice the @butternut squash{1} in half lengthways (no need to peel!) and scoop out the seeds. Slice it widthways into about 1cm thick pieces, then chop it into 1cm cubes. Halve, peel and chop the @red onion{1}(halved and sliced into wedges) into wedges - about four wedges per half.

Spread the butternut squash and onion out on a #baking tray{}. Drizzle over half the @honey{15%ml}, a good glug of @olive oil{3%tbsp}, a pinch of @chilli flakes{pinch} (careful, they're hot!), @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to ensure an even coating. Place on the top shelf of your oven and roast until soft and starting to caramelise, about ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). In a #mixing bowl{}, combine the garlic, oil and remaining honey. Season with a good pinch of salt and pepper. Add the @British pork loin steaks{2} to the bowl and use your hands to coat the pork well in the marinade.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands, board and equipment after handling raw meat.

Heat a #frying pan{} on medium heat (no oil). When hot, add the pork steaks and fry until golden brown, ~{1-2%minutes} on each side.

> TIP: Leave the excess marinade in the bowl, we'll use it later! We will finish the pork steaks in the oven, so don't fry them for too long or they may overcook!

When they are done, simply remove the pan from the heat and wait till the veg is ready for them.

When the veg has been cooking for 20-25 min and is crispy, turn it and lay the pork steaks on top, ensuring you tip any marinade leftover from the bowl onto the #tray{}. Scatter over the @pumpkin seeds{15%g}. Return the tray to the oven to cook for a further ~{8-10%minutes}.

> TIP: The pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When the pork is done, remove it to a #plate{} and cover it loosely with foil to rest while you finish up.

Serve the roasted veggies in #bowls{}. Crumble over half the @feta cheese{100%g}(crumbled). Slice the pork into 1cm strips and lay on top of the veg before crumbling over the remaining feta. Pop a handful of @baby leaf mix{50%g} on the side and pour over any juices from the roasting tray - the flavour is delicious. Enjoy!